snippet.textDisplay:
"For Allmight's strongest attack we're going to reference his basic attack from the first episode that is weaker than almost every single thing he does throughout the next three seasons."

I'm not really bothered by the channel, it's fun, it's bringing to life our childhood of mashing action figures together.  But there's this weird bias where the show takes one of the characters and deliberately ignores half their feats or abilities.  Or worse, they take some obscure throw away in a comic and use that to claim power a character has never shown because the physics of the throw away were impossible.

It's become more obvious over the years you guys have a picked winner and then tweak the stats to justify that, so maybe stop worrying about trying to "prove" your math at the end.
snippet.textOriginal:
"For Allmight's strongest attack we're going to reference his basic attack from the first episode that is weaker than almost every single thing he does throughout the next three seasons."

I'm not really bothered by the channel, it's fun, it's bringing to life our childhood of mashing action figures together.  But there's this weird bias where the show takes one of the characters and deliberately ignores half their feats or abilities.  Or worse, they take some obscure throw away in a comic and use that to claim power a character has never shown because the physics of the throw away were impossible.

It's become more obvious over the years you guys have a picked winner and then tweak the stats to justify that, so maybe stop worrying about trying to "prove" your math at the end.

snippet.textDisplay:
Honestly I’m disappointed they lowballed the hell out of Guy. Most substantial Naruto characters have casually hypersonic techniques. Guy becomes insane when you put numbers to his techniques because it’s all just quick hands in the end.

Asakujaku: Morning Peacock - is basically Guy whiffing punches at terminal velocity. Which at bare minimum is Mach 12 that dude can launch dozens of almost instantaneously.

Hirudorah: Afternoon Tiger - Guy is punching you with enough relativistic force from a shockwave of air pressure that’s in the gigatons. A literally Nuke. But while All Might has the enhance strength of OFA to change the weather in a similar feat. Guy is going off of relativistic speed with his attacks, in order for a single man to punch with the aftershock of the world’s most powerful nuclear warhead like a Tsar bomb... so here’s some math.


E=0.5mv2 which represents the the kinetic energy of a moving object.

E=210000 TJ (terrajoules) the energy behind the blast radius of a Tsar bomb.

Let’s say Guy’s hand weighs, 3.6 kg

E=0.5(3.6)V2=210000(1000000000000)
Divide 210000(10000000000000) by 0.5(3.6)
V= 341565025.5 =1.1c

Guy’s hand needs to be at minimum moving 110x the speed of light.

Which makes sense given when Guy performs Hirudora you never actually see him perform the said punch.

Then there’s Night Guy.
This technically on paper looks like a hyped up drop kick but against a FTL threat like 6 Path’s Madara it’s much more than that. The fact that literal space bent the knee for Guy means that his drop kick warped the space around it. For Guy to perform this with just Taijutsu, his kick needed to basically transcend a plank length (shortest measurement of distance in the universe), in less time than a Plank instant (shortest measurement of time in existence) in which he violated the very basic concept of speed when Guy drop kicked him. At that Speed Night Guy is basically unavoidable. At that point the speed and impact of Night Guy would virtually be incalculable.
snippet.textOriginal:
Honestly I’m disappointed  they lowballed the hell out of Guy. Most substantial Naruto characters have casually hypersonic techniques. Guy becomes insane when you put numbers to his techniques because it’s all just quick hands in the end.

Asakujaku: Morning Peacock - is basically Guy whiffing punches at terminal velocity. Which at bare minimum is Mach 12 that dude can launch dozens of almost instantaneously.

Hirudorah: Afternoon Tiger - Guy is punching you with enough relativistic force from a shockwave of air pressure that’s in the gigatons. A literally Nuke. But while All Might has the enhance strength of OFA to change the weather in a similar feat. Guy is going off of relativistic speed with his attacks, in order for a single man to punch with the aftershock of the world’s most powerful nuclear warhead like a Tsar bomb... so here’s some math.


E=0.5mv2 which represents the the kinetic energy of a moving object.

E=210000 TJ (terrajoules) the energy behind the blast radius of a Tsar bomb.

Let’s say Guy’s hand weighs, 3.6 kg

E=0.5(3.6)V2=210000(1000000000000)
Divide 210000(10000000000000) by 0.5(3.6)
V= 341565025.5 =1.1c

Guy’s hand needs to be at minimum moving 110x the speed of light.

Which makes sense given when Guy performs Hirudora you never actually see him perform the said punch.

Then there’s Night Guy.
This technically on paper looks like a hyped up drop kick but against a FTL threat like 6 Path’s Madara it’s much more than that. The fact that literal space bent the knee for Guy means that his drop kick warped the space around it. For Guy to perform this with just Taijutsu, his kick needed to basically transcend a plank length (shortest measurement of distance in the universe), in less time than a Plank instant (shortest measurement of time in existence) in which he violated the very basic concept of speed when Guy drop kicked him. At that Speed Night Guy is basically unavoidable. At that point the speed and impact of Night Guy would virtually be incalculable.
